So it has already defined some default value. You then define the `filterChain` bean to override some of the default value based on your application security requirement.

&gt; How it sets the values in multi-calls without overwriting the previous
&gt; values? what is this approach name in Java? Can I do the same with my
&gt; objects?

It depends on the implementation of that method. Some method will overwrite the previous value such as `http.csrf().disable()` while some method will add one more configuration to the related `SecurityConfigurer` such as `http.authorizeRequests().mvcMatchers(&quot;api/**&quot;).authenticated()`.


This approach is use method chaining to build a [DSL-like API][3] for configuring the `HttpSecurity`.


&gt; Is there a way that I can see what are its current values?

As `HttpSecurity` is a bean , that means you can define a spring bean and inject it into this bean such that you can navigate and access its internal structure to see its current value. 

For example, implement a `CommandLineRunner` which will execute at the application startup is a nice way to go : 

``` java
@Component
public class MyCommandLineRunner implement CommandLineRunner {
	
	@Autowired
	private HttpSecurity httpSecurity;

	public void run(String... args) throws Exception {
		//access httpSecurity to see if current value.
	}

}
```

